iginal equations, we can write:\n\nFrom a² = b +6 --> b = a² -6\n\nFrom b² = c +6 --> c = b² -6\n\nFrom c² = a +6 --> a = c² -6\n\nTherefore, perhaps substituting these into each other:\n\na = c² -6 = (b² -6)^2 -6\n\nBut b = a² -6, so:\n\na = ( (a² -6)^2 -6 )^2 -6\n\nThis seems to lead us again to a high-degree equation.\n\nPerhaps, given that this is getting too complex, let's consider that perhaps a + b + c is an integer, maybe 0, 6, or something.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps let's assume that a + b + c = k, and then try to find k.\n\nFrom earlier, we had:\n\nFrom adding the equations: a² + b² + c² = S +18.\n\nAlso, we had a² + b² + c² = S² -2(ab + bc + ca).\n\nTherefore:\n\nS² -2(ab + bc + ca) = S +18.\n\nBut from earlier, we had:\n\nab + bc + ca = (S² - S -18)/2.\n\nThus, substituting into the first equation:\n\nS² - 2*( (S² - S -18)/2 ) = S +18.\n\nSimplify:\n\nS² - (S² - S -18) = S +18.\n\nWhich becomes:\n\nS² - S² + S +18 = S +18.\n\nWhich simplifies to:\n\nS +18 = S +18.\n\nAgain, which is an identity, so no new information.\n\nTherefore, perhaps I need a different strategy.\n\nLet me consider that since a, b, c are roots of some polynomial, perhaps let's compute the sum S.\n\nFrom the equations:\n\na² = b +6\n\nb² = c +6\n\nc² = a +6\n\nThus, adding all three:\n\na² + b² + c² = a + b + c + 18.\n\nBut from before, we have:\n\na² + b² + c² = S +18.\n\nThus, perhaps substituting into the above:\n\nS +18 = S +18.\n\nAgain, nothing new.\n\nTherefore, perhaps another approach is needed.\n\nLet me think about the product of the equations.\n\nFrom:\n\na² = b +6 --> b = a² -6\n\nb² = c +6 --> c = b² -6\n\nc² = a +6 --> a = c² -6\n\nTherefore, perhaps substitute each into the next.\n\nThus, substitute b into c:\n\nc = (a² -6)^2 -6\n\nThen substitute c into a:\n\na = [ (a² -6)^2 -6 ]² -6\n\nThis is the same high-degree equation as before, which is difficult to solve.\n\nTherefore, perhaps let's think of another approach.\n\nLet me denote S = a + b + c.\n\nWe need to find