nThus:\n\nt² =3t² -2t +162 +36 S.\n\nBring all terms to left side:\n\nt² -3t² +2t -162 -36 S=0.\n\nSimplify:\n\n-2t² +2t -162 -36 S=0.\n\nMultiply both sides by (-1):\n\n2t² -2t +162 +36 S=0.\n\nDivide both sides by 2:\n\nt² -t +81 +18 S=0.\n\nThus:\n\nt² - t +81 +18 S=0.\n\nBut t = a b c, which we can express in terms of S.\n\nBut perhaps we can find another relation.\n\nWait, perhaps from the equation earlier, t = a b c.\n\nBut perhaps from the given equations, we can find t.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps consider that from the original equations, we can write:\n\nFrom a² = b +6 --> b = a² -6.\n\nSimilarly, c = b² -6 = (a² -6)^2 -6.\n\nAnd a = c² -6.\n\nThus, perhaps substitute b and c into a.\n\nSo:\n\na = [ (a² -6)^2 -6 ]² -6.\n\nWhich is:\n\na = [ (a^4 -12a² +36 -6 ) ]² -6.\n\nSimplify:\n\na = [ (a^4 -12a² +30 ) ]² -6.\n\nCompute this:\n\na = (a^4 -12a² +30 )² -6.\n\nThis is a degree 8 equation, which is even more complex.\n\nTherefore, perhaps we need to find another approach.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps note that if we add all three original equations, we have:\n\na² + b² + c² = S +18.\n\nBut perhaps we can also note that from the product of the equations:\n\n(a b c)^2 = (a +6)(b +6)(c +6).\n\nBut perhaps let's compute the RHS:\n\n(a +6)(b +6)(c +6) = a b c +6a b +6a c +6b c +36a +36b +36c +216.\n\nThus, equation becomes:\n\n(a b c)^2 = a b c +6a b +6a c +6b c +36a +36b +36c +216.\n\nLet me denote t = a b c, so equation is:\n\nt² = t +6(ab + ac + bc) +36(a +b +c) +216.\n\nBut from earlier, ab + bc + ca = (t² - t -18)/2.\n\nTherefore, substitute:\n\nt² = t +6*( (t² - t -18)/2 ) +36 S +216.\n\nSimplify:\n\nt² = t +3*(t² - t -18) +36 S +216.\n\nCompute:\n\nt² = t +3t² -3t -54 +36 S +216.\n\nSimplify:\n\nt² =3t² -2t +162 +36 S.\n\nBring all terms to left:\n\nt² -3t² +2t -162 -36 S=0.\n\nSimplify:\n\n-2t² +2t -162 -36 S=0.\n\nMultiply both sides by (-1):\n\n2t² -2t +162 +36 S=0.\n\nDivide both sides by 2:\n\nt² -t +81 +18 S=0.\n\nThus, t² - t +81 +18 S=0.\n\nBut since t